section.p:
From what I can tell, the basic challenge is that calculators behave in a way that doesn't always match up with how students think the calculator should behave. Here is an example:
\frac{2 + 6}{3 + 1}
When students read this in their minds, they see it as plus divided by plus and proceed to press the following buttons:

image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture}
	\draw (0,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$2$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (1,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$+$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (2,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$6$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (3,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$\div$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (4,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$3$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (5,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$+$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (6,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$1$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
	\draw (7,0) node[anchor=center] {\strut \texttt{$=$}} ++ (-0.3,-0.3) rectangle ++ (0.6,0.6); 
\end{tikzpicture}

\begin{tikzpicture}
